issue.title: Maybe it's easier for us to support BYD cars?
issue.body:
BYD is a famous vehicle manufacturing company in China, they released the open API just a few days ago, see: [http://oip.byd.com/sites/developer/index.html](http://oip.byd.com/sites/developer/index.html). That's the API document: 
[比亚迪智慧开放平台API说明书V1.0.5.pdf](https://github.com/commaai/openpilot/files/2363166/API.V1.0.5.pdf)
We can get the whole vehicle information easily by the open API, but we can not operate the vehicle's steering wheel and throttle right now. There may be opportunities here, because of BYD's open mind. Maybe it's easier for us to support BYD cars, right?

comment.body:
2023 BYD Atto 3 models are currently equipped with advanced driver assistance systems (ADAS) including autonomous emergency braking (AEB), lane-keep assist, and adaptive cruise control with stop/go

May be it could be reviewed

issue.title: rawgpsd died during test run
issue.body:
### Describe the bug

RawGPS died and it forced me to take control, I don't know how to reproduce it reliably, sorry!

### Provide a route where the issue occurs

e1107f9d04dfb1e2|2023-10-09--21-02-26--0

### openpilot version

0.9.5

### Additional info

_No response_

comment.body:
> > > I was getting this same error when I was working on a custom feature. I had a made a new daemon that updated once a minute. When I added 'liveLocationKalman' to the SubMaster, I would randomly get this error on startup. I re-implemented the feature using the 'LastGPSPosition' param and the error went away.
> > 
> > 
> > I don't see how this could cause any issues with rawgpsd. If you have a branch that reproduces this reliably, that would be very helpful.
> 
> Reverted to using `liveLocationKalman` and now I don't get any errors. I guess I somehow got into an error state that resolved itself with a fresh install? Not sure.

I don’t suggest using liveLocationKalman for any realtime gps stuff, it’s better to use gpsLocation and gpsLocationExternal (C3) otherwise the location won’t be updated properly :(
